# blog-app-mui-frontend Code Style

Stack: **Next.js 15 (App Router) + React 19 + MUI v7**. SWR for data, React Hook
Form + Zod for forms, Tiptap for the editor. This project is built on the
Minimals.cc template — match the template's existing conventions, do not impose
a different house style on it.

## Naming & file structure

Files and folders are **kebab-case** — never PascalCase:

```
src/components/custom-popover/
  custom-popover.tsx     — the component
  index.ts               — re-export: export * from './custom-popover'
  types.ts               — types for this component (only if it has its own)
  utils.ts               — pure helpers (formatting, sx mapping), no JSX
  use-popover.ts         — co-located hook
  classes.ts / styles.tsx — style tokens / styled() wrappers
```

- Components: kebab-case file, named export (e.g. `export function CustomPopover`).
  PascalCase is for the symbol, never the filename.
- Co-locate `const.ts` / `types.ts` / `utils.ts` next to a non-trivial component
  instead of inlining large data/type blocks.
- Do NOT rename existing files to PascalCase. The whole codebase is kebab-case;
  keep it consistent.

## Sections isolation

`src/sections/` holds page-specific feature components. A section must NOT import
another section (`sections/blog` importing from `sections/home` is a violation).
If two sections need the same component, lift it into `src/components/`.

## Styling

- Use MUI `sx` + the theme palette (`theme.palette`, `alpha(...)`) for borders,
  hover, text — so primary-color and light/dark switching work predictably.
- Static brand tokens (e.g. a fixed gradient) may live in CSS next to the
  section and be `@import`-ed from `src/global.css`. Don't hardcode palette
  colors in CSS.

## Forms

All forms use React Hook Form + Zod via `src/components/hook-form/`. Use the
`RHF*` field components (`RHFTextField`, etc.) — never raw MUI inputs in a form.

## Routing & env

- Routes live in `src/app/` (App Router). Navigate via `src/routes/hooks`
  (re-exports of `next/navigation`) and path constants in `src/routes/paths.ts`.
- Env vars are build-time, prefixed `NEXT_PUBLIC_`, read via `process.env`
  (NOT `import.meta.env` / `VITE_`).
- Dev-only routes/pages use the `.dev.tsx` extension (registered as routable
  only in development in `next.config.mjs`); the component gallery under
  `/examples` is reachable at `/dev/examples` in dev and absent from prod.

## TypeScript

- No `any`. Reuse shared types from `src/types/` (`Post`, `Comment`, `User`,
  `FileMeta`, API response types). For opaque catch values use `unknown` + narrow
  (`error instanceof Error ? error.message : ...`).
- `import type { Foo } from "..."` for type-only imports.
- The `src/` alias resolves via tsconfig `baseUrl`; `examples/` via a path alias.

## Imports

Grouped and sorted (enforced by `import/order` + `perfectionist`):
external packages → internal `src/` aliases → local relative → CSS last.
No circular dependencies — `import/no-cycle` is an error (verify: `npx madge
--circular --extensions ts,tsx src`).

## Linting

- `yarn lint` must be 0 errors. Author folders (`actions`, `auth`,
  `sections/{blog,admin,portfolio}`, `app`) are held to error-level
  `unused-vars`; vendored template code stays at warn until cleaned per-folder.
- Don't silence rules with `eslint-disable` / `@ts-ignore` to push code through.
  Fix the cause.

## Dead code

Vendored template code that no live route uses is either removed or isolated
(see `/examples`). Don't add new files to the dead-but-kept template areas;
build features in `src/sections/` + `src/app/`.
